A few words of advice from someone who has bought and sold many guns including here on Armslist.
1) When a listing reads NO TRADES, that means the seller doesn't want your S&W, FNS or Glock in exchange for their gun no matter how great you say your gun is.2) "No low ball offers" means don't offer the seller $400 for a gun with a value of $500. And throwing in "CASH" doesn't help. Stop it. You think I would take personal check from a person I don't know?3) If you ever begin a text with "Wassuup" to ask about a gun for sale or type an email as though it were a text, I will personally never sell you any gun even if you offered more than I'm asking.4) Don't be a pathetic, urgent & desperate buyer. It comes across like want this gun to pull off a hit over the weekend.

title: For Sale:  Megastar .45/10mm
postcontent: The Megastar pistol is a heavy, powerful pistol, which appeared on the markets in 1993. It was designed and manufactured by the Spanish company Star Bonifacio Echeverria SA, and its design is based on the previous guns by the same manufacturer, such as Star 30M. Production of the Megastar was completed in the late 1990s.Megastar is a recoil operated, locked breech semi-automatic pistol. It uses a Browning High-Power type locking system with tilting barrel. Megastar is a hammer fired pistol, with double action trigger and ambidextrous, slide mounted safety-decocker lever. The safety lever has three positions: upper one for "fire" mode, red dot is shown; medium one for "safe" mode, this withdraws and locks the firing pin; and the lower one for safe decocking (after decocking safety lever springs back to the "safe" position). Megastar also features a magazine disconnect safety which does not allow to fire the gun withouth magazine in the place. Megastar slide and frame are made from the steel, and like other latest Star pistols, Megastar has internal slide rails, instead of more usual external rails. This pistol features non-ajustable sights. Magazine capacity is quite impressive, especially when speaking about the period of the early 1990s, and is 12 rounds of .45ACP or 14 rounds of 10mm Auto.Overall, Megastar represents one of the strongest designs in auto-pistols, heavy but powerful and built to last forewer. Heavy weight also helps to control the recoil of the powerful cartridges used.

title: For Sale:  M1 Garand with uncut Dash 3 Op Rod
postcontent:
It should be obvious that most of the Garand ads on Armslist are bogus scams offering a $1,000 or $2,000 Garand for $700 with a generic location like "North Carolina" instead of the town. The sellers won't meet in person and usually want the rifle shipped to some other address (My favorite is "I'm buying this for my dad. I'll pay for it, but can you ship it to him?). This is not one of those ads. My strong preference is for a face to face, cash sale. Because of the number of scamers that have responded to this ad I will only ship this rifle if it is paid for with a USPS money order. And I will only ship it to a valid FFL (01 or 03 C&R)... not some other address.
Not thrilled to sell this. However, I run the site gear-report.com and just bought a surplus Humvee as a field vehicle for the website... but I had not budgeted for it. So, I have to liquidate a few assets to cover the cost. If you go to my site and use the search bar at the top right to search for "Garand" you will find an article with video about this Service Grade Garand and articles about the other Garand I have for sale.On my website you will find a video of unboxing this M1 Garand and an article and video of the other Garand I have for sale. Just search for "garand" in the search box on my site.M1 Garand with Springfield receiver in the 3.08M serial range.Brand new CMP stock with a couple of coats of BLO/mineral spirits scrubbed in. A friend who is knowledgable in Garands told me the following about it:-Fairly rare WWII M1 Garand 3 SA Curve Side Op Rod. D35382 3 SA marked with NO relief cut.Dash 3 "Curve Side" rods were used from approx Mar '41 thru Oct '42 on WWII M1's(ser# range 197812 thru 1,000,000). Curve Side Op Rods have a distinctive curve on the hump forward of the charging handle, hence curve vs flat side.
-All Springfield parts except HRA-W rear sight.
-Trigger pack appears to be NOS Springfield with no evidence it has been apart.-SA 8/53 barrel measured 2 at the muzzle, 3 at the throat.
Not interested in trades or low-ball offers.Strongly prefer a face to face sale in Burlington, NC. I am willing to ship to your FFL or C&R at your expense ONLY if payment is made with a USPS money order.  I had a rather convincing prospective buyer try to sucker me on a remote deal with payment by some othe means. Not dealing with that crap again.

title: For Sale:  GM INLAND MFG DIVISION 1941 M1A1 Carbine Paratrooper with M8A bayonet
postcontent:
It should be obvious that most of the M1 Carbine and Garand ads on Armslist are bogus scams offering a $1,000 or $2,000 collector piece for $700 with a generic location like "North Carolina" instead of the town. The sellers won't meet in person and usually want the rifle shipped to some other address (My favorite is "I'm buying this for my dad. I'll pay for it, but can you ship it to him?). This is not one of those ads. My strong preference is for a face to face, cash sale. Because of the number of scamers that have responded to this ad I will only ship this rifle if it is paid for with a USPS money order. And I will only ship it to a valid FFL (01 or 03 C&R)... not some other address.
Not thrilled to sell this. However, I run the site gear-report.com and just bought a surplus Humvee as a field vehicle for the website... but I had not budgeted for it. So, I have to liquidate a few assets to cover the cost. If you go to my site and use the search bar at the top right to search for "M1A1" you will find an article about this M1 Carbine.
U.S.A. Model M1A1 "paratrooper" semiautomatic carbine # 109xxx (.30 Carbine) mfg. by Inland (General Motors) in 1942 with 11-43 dated Underwood barrel. Excellent condition with full Parkerized finish remaining on all metal and having an excellent bore.
